rComments: Dr. Cirelli was a great lecturer in the sense that she really is clear and goes into depth when explaining concepts. I definitely learnt alot from her class. Her exams are lecture and textbook based, definitely do-able but you need to study, memorize well and apply concepts to do well. The blog assignment is marked hard by TAs. Overall great course

Although this prof is a great lecturer, there are many things that could be improved on. Her exam questions are made especially tricky... you can leave the exam feeling so confident but ended up doing so bad. For assignment she stresses to keep it in a word limit for easy marks but the feedbacks all say "elaborate more" or "be more specific".
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read']

rComments: Easy class if you can memorize. There is a lot of content, but it is easy and interesting . She delivers the info in a clear way.
teacherRatingTags: ['Gives good feedback', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Participation matters']

rComments: Very good prof, very straightforward. Just show up to class and review the lectures. Exams are easy. not very heavy on textbook.

Makes the exam questions unnecessarily wordy but I'm pretty much convinced that she does this just so it's hard to understand. Each question is also like five sentences long. You literally forget the beginning of the question before you reach the end. Even though this course was weboptioned you still have to go to class because she uses TopHat..

So she does take long to explain one concept, but at least you fully understand it by the end of class. The exams are very straight forward, study the lec notes and review the textbook chapters and you should be good. The content of the course is not hard. If you memorize the ages of specific developmental stages then you will do well.

She expected you thoroughly summarize a research article she assigned and make a blog post about it all within only 400-500 words. Which is near impossible. She then decided to grade the entire assignment out of only 14. So if you literally make a small mistake (apa error) and lose 1 mark you lose 7% of the assignment grade. Where is the logic?

Her midterms are only 30 questions, so you know it or you don't. The final exam was half cumulative and half focused on the last portion of the course. All lectures were min 2 hours, can get a bit overwhelming but she's not bad at lecturing. You also have to go to class because she uses Top Hat which you will have to pay of $30 for.
